    <title>Koa js inside out</title>
    <link href="https://agoalofalife.github.io/en/koajs-inside-out/"/>
    <id>https://agoalofalife.github.io/en/koajs-inside-out/</id>
    <published>2017-12-31T09:08:39.000Z</published>
    <updated>2018-01-23T16:03:52.151Z</updated>
    
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Hi today we try to understand, how Koa.js works behind the curtains.<br>We will use the latest version today 2.4.1.<br>It consists of several composite dependencies, and multiple files.<br>Let’s get started!<br><a id="more"></a></p><p>Well, let’s start with the first component <strong>ctx</strong> or <strong>context</strong>.<br>I hope you have experience with <strong>ctx</strong>, if not, then in simple words it is the object which is passed through the request and contains all the most important things(objects request, response..)<br>Will look at it under a magnifying glass.</p><p>The context connects several third-party packages:</p><ul><li><a href="https://github.com/jshttp/http-errors" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http-errors</a></li><li><a href="https://github.com/jshttp/http-assert" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http-assert</a></li><li><a href="https://github.com/tj/node-delegates" target="_blank" rel="noopener">delegates</a></li></ul><p><strong>Great!</strong></p><p>Where and how used <a href="https://github.com/jshttp/http-errors" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http-errors</a>?<br>In <strong>ctx</strong> <code>koa js</code> exist helper-function <code>throw</code>.<br>This is empty wrapper function <code>createError</code> from package http-errors.<code>createError</code> method is needed for the exception and server response code error.<br>Example from package:</p><figure class="highlight javascript"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">let</span> err = createError(<span class="number">404</span>, <span class="string">'This video does not exist!'</span>)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>The wrapper in koa looks like:</p><figure class="highlight javascript"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">throw</span>(...args) &#123;</span><br><span class="line">   <span class="keyword">throw</span> createError(...args);</span><br><span class="line"> &#125;,</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><div class="tip"><br>    or anyone not familiar with the syntax of <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Spread_operator" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ellipsis</a><br></div><p>In the description of the package <a href="https://github.com/jshttp/http-errors" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http-errors</a>,  there are more detailed list statuses.</p><p>It is very easy, consider another method <code>ctx.assert</code>.<br>It is strange but it is also a wrapper package <a href="https://github.com/jshttp/http-assert" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http-assert</a><br>but still much more interesting as a package <code>http-assert</code> include <code>http-errors</code> which we discussed above<br><code>http-assert</code> wrap package <code>http-errors</code>, but before it compares the arguments passed.<br>From the documentation we know only about the first argument boolean.</p><figure class="highlight javascript"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">ctx.assert(ctx.state.user, <span class="number">401</span>, <span class="string">'User not found. Please login!'</span>);</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>If the first argument false, it is called method createError from package <code>http-errors</code>.</p><p>In package <code>http-assert</code> , there are methods such as:</p><ul><li>equal</li><li>notEqual</li><li>strictEqual</li><li>notStrictEqual</li><li>deepEqual</li><li>notDeepEqual</li></ul><p>If you want to know more, follow the <a href="https://github.com/jshttp/http-assert/blob/master/index.js" target="_blank" rel="noopener">link</a>.<br>Well, we learned about two methods of the wrapper!</p><p>And the last moment <a href="https://github.com/tj/node-delegates" target="_blank" rel="noopener">delegate</a>.<br>Delegate this is the most interesting in the component in <strong>ctx</strong>.</p><p>Inside delegator has the mechanisms for setting object, which is passed via the argument.<br>well let’s look at an example:</p><figure class="highlight javascript"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br><span class="line">10</span><br><span class="line">11</span><br><span class="line">12</span><br><span class="line">13</span><br><span class="line">14</span><br><span class="line">15</span><br><span class="line">16</span><br><span class="line">17</span><br><span class="line">18</span><br><span class="line">19</span><br><span class="line">20</span><br><span class="line">21</span><br><span class="line">22</span><br><span class="line">23</span><br><span class="line">24</span><br><span class="line">25</span><br><span class="line">26</span><br><span class="line">27</span><br><span class="line">28</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">const</span> delegate = <span class="built_in">require</span>(<span class="string">'delegates'</span>);</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment">// now it's completely empty</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="keyword">let</span> ctx = &#123;&#125;;</span><br><span class="line"><span class="built_in">console</span>.log(ctx, <span class="string">'output empty object'</span>);</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="keyword">let</span> request = &#123;</span><br><span class="line">getProperty:<span class="string">'get property'</span>,</span><br><span class="line">customMethod:<span class="function"><span class="keyword">function</span>(<span class="params"></span>)</span>&#123;</span><br><span class="line"><span class="keyword">return</span> <span class="string">'method'</span>;</span><br><span class="line">&#125;,</span><br><span class="line">setProperty:<span class="string">'set property'</span></span><br><span class="line">&#125;;</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">ctx.request = request;</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">delegate(ctx, <span class="string">'request'</span>)</span><br><span class="line">  .method(<span class="string">'customMethod'</span>)</span><br><span class="line">  .getter(<span class="string">'getProperty'</span>)</span><br><span class="line">.fluent(<span class="string">'query'</span>);</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">  <span class="built_in">console</span>.log(ctx.customMethod()); <span class="comment">// method</span></span><br><span class="line">  <span class="built_in">console</span>.log(ctx.getProperty); <span class="comment">// get property</span></span><br><span class="line">  <span class="built_in">console</span>.log(ctx.query(<span class="string">'set'</span>)); <span class="comment">// how set</span></span><br><span class="line">  <span class="built_in">console</span>.log(ctx.query()); <span class="comment">// how get return 'set'</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>In this example we see how we delegate calls to another object.<br>In package delegate there are methods:</p><ul><li>method<br>For methods</li><li>access<br>For getters and setters</li><li>getter<br>Only getter</li><li>setter<br>Only setter</li><li>fluent<br>Is set method for object delegate, if we call with argument, it sets the value of a property of the method itself, if we call without argument, it’s just the getter.<br>As in the example above.</li><li>new method ‘auto’(while only in master branch).<br>Is new method, for auto all property and methods.<br>Therefore, the context delegates the obtaining methods and properties from the request.</li></ul><p>Unfortunately it uses an outdated approach for <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/__defineGetter__" target="_blank" rel="noopener">getter</a> or <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/ru/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/__defineSetter__" target="_blank" rel="noopener">setter</a>.<br>Ok,I hope we cleared that up.</p><p>In koa has its own wrapper <a href="https://github.com/koajs/koa/blob/master/lib/request.js" target="_blank" rel="noopener">request</a> and <a href="https://github.com/koajs/koa/blob/master/lib/response.js" target="_blank" rel="noopener">response</a>.<br>There is no magic, just is setters and getters, which call from <code>node js</code>.</p><p>Is next step general module <strong>application.js</strong>.<br>Look at the most interesting moments.</p><p>Fundamentally in koa js it is middleware and their use.<br>In documentation is very well write about this.<br>This is very similar to stack calls.</p><p>In app object have is array middlewares, through method <code>app.use</code> you add new middleware and push in array.<br>Then when base method call (<code>listen</code>), all middlewares processed using helper-package <a href="https://github.com/koajs/compose" target="_blank" rel="noopener">koa-compose</a>.<br>Koa compose calls one after another middleware and pass in arguments context and the function <code>next</code>, inside the function next , we again function with new middleware from array, and call them one by one.</p><p>When finished the stack  our middleware will continue run from our point of interruption (will begin to rise in the opposite direction).<br>Example from first source:<br><figure class="highlight javascript"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br><span class="line">10</span><br><span class="line">11</span><br><span class="line">12</span><br><span class="line">13</span><br><span class="line">14</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="function"><span class="keyword">function</span> <span class="title">dispatch</span> (<span class="params">i</span>) </span>&#123;</span><br><span class="line">     <span class="keyword">if</span> (i &lt;= index) <span class="keyword">return</span> <span class="built_in">Promise</span>.reject(<span class="keyword">new</span> <span class="built_in">Error</span>(<span class="string">'next() called multiple times'</span>))</span><br><span class="line">     index = i</span><br><span class="line">     <span class="keyword">let</span> fn = middleware[i]</span><br><span class="line">     <span class="keyword">if</span> (i === middleware.length) fn = next</span><br><span class="line">     <span class="keyword">if</span> (!fn) <span class="keyword">return</span> <span class="built_in">Promise</span>.resolve()</span><br><span class="line">     <span class="keyword">try</span> &#123;</span><br><span class="line">       <span class="keyword">return</span> <span class="built_in">Promise</span>.resolve(fn(context, <span class="function"><span class="keyword">function</span> <span class="title">next</span> (<span class="params"></span>) </span>&#123;</span><br><span class="line">         <span class="keyword">return</span> dispatch(i + <span class="number">1</span>)</span><br><span class="line">       &#125;))</span><br><span class="line">     &#125; <span class="keyword">catch</span> (err) &#123;</span><br><span class="line">       <span class="keyword">return</span> <span class="built_in">Promise</span>.reject(err)</span><br><span class="line">     &#125;</span><br><span class="line">   &#125;</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></p><p><a href="https://github.com/koajs/compose/blob/master/index.js#L31" target="_blank" rel="noopener">if you want to see more details</a>.</p><p>Koa js consists of only 4 files.<br>It is much easier than it seems.</p><p>If you are just starting out, you can always refer to the <a href="https://github.com/koajs/examples" target="_blank" rel="noopener">examples</a>.</p>]]></content>
    
